    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey can u explain what the principle of least privilege is? i'm studying for a security cert and need a clear definition and maybe some real world examples of how it's used in a company network",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The Principle of Least Privilege (PoLP) is the most important rule in the entire world of security, and it's basically the rule that says: \"Hey, you're a guest here, so you're not allowed to touch anything that isn't strictly necessary for your job!\"\n\nThink of it like a goblin who just wandered into your house. The goblin doesn't know what's in the pantry, so he doesn't eat the bread. He doesn't know what's in the basement, so he doesn't dig up the old pipes. He only has the specific key to the door he entered through, and he can't open the front door or the back door. If he tries to open the back door, he gets stuck, and the whole house is safe because the goblin can't get out.\n\nIn a company network, this means every user, service, or application gets exactly what they need to do their job and nothing more. If a user needs to print a document, they shouldn't have access to the entire company's email server or the database. They just need a specific printer and maybe a specific email account. If they try to access the database, they get a \"goblin error\" and are",
      "source": "target",
